0.1 Introduction

For improved readability, majority of the code snippets have been initially concealed. The option to display all code chunks is in the upper right corner, next to the title.

In this project student housing data in the academic year 2022/2023 was analyzed. The objective is to find suitable private accommodation among the collaborators of UP Å SD that provide private accommodation for students.

Private accomodation is a solution for the majority of UP students. Out of 5745 students, only 439 can get a place to stay in the university dormitories.

data <- data.frame(
  Category = c("Dormitory beds", "Additional Beds Needed"),
  Count = c(94 + 160 + 130 + 55, 5745 - (94 + 160 + 130 + 55) )
)

data$Percentage <- data$Count / 5745 * 100


ggplot(data, aes(x = "", y = Count, fill = Category)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity") +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  labs(title = "There are 5745 students at the university in the academic year 2022/2023.") +
  labs(fill = "Category") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Dormitory beds" = "#A8CCC9", "Additional Beds Needed" = "#75B9BE")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_text(aes(label = Count), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5))

Sources: UP Å tudentski domovi,, University UP in numbers

0.1.1 Loading the data

The analyzed dataset is contained in stanovanja2.tsv. The data was received by the courtesy of UP Å tudentski domovi.

Due to difficulties with loading the original file, a .tsv file was created:

data <- read.table("/home/sasha/r/stanovanja2.tsv", sep = "\t", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

Since the dataframe contains some info that is not needed for the purposes of this project, columns 1, 3, 4 and 5 that contain personal information of the landlords are omitted.

data<-data %>% 
  select(-c(Ime, Priimek, Naslov, Posta, Kraj))

A function for editing the dataframe output is created to save time making the output more easily readable.

nice_table<-function(df, pageLength = NULL) {
  
  #since pageLength option is not always needed,
  #options list has to be modified based on arguments provided
  options_list<-list(scrollX = TRUE)
  
  if (!is.null(pageLength)) {
    options_list$pageLength<-pageLength
  }
  
  DT::datatable(df, options = options_list)
}
data %>% 
  nice_table(., 5)

0.2.1 Email addresses

Converting email-address to lowercase:

data$elektronski_naslov<-tolower(data$elektronski_naslov)
data %>%
  nice_table(., 5)

Our following problem is that during the conversion process to uppercase in the original data and this conversion to lowercase resulted in incorrect address if it originally contained both uppercase and lowercase letters (which is not that usual, but it is a possibility). This means we canâ€™t really know if the data is usable or not.

However, gmail mail service offers a feature that can help us a bit. Since it shows existing accounts upon typing in the email adress, we can confirm if the adress exists before even writing the email.

Gmail confirms the email message.

Letâ€™s extract the flats that have a gmail adress, which ensures that the email address can be confirmed easily:

data$email_provider<-gsub("^.*@([^.]+)\\..*$", "\\1", data$elektronski_naslov)

data %>% 
  select(elektronski_naslov, email_provider) %>% 
  nice_table(., 5)

So here are the values for email providers:

emails<-table(data$email_provider) %>% 
  data.frame(provider = names(.), frequency = as.numeric(.)) %>% 
  select(provider, frequency)
emails %>% 
  nice_table()

Letâ€™s visualize this, excluding the empty values (i.e.Â â€œâ€œ,â€/â€œ) and the apparent mistake in case ofâ€apartmaji@slavnik-siâ€ value:

We can immediately see that majority of the email adresses are gmail, which makes majority of the data usable. By adding email_provider column, we can filter such data later on more easily.

0.2.2 Extracting the town

Probably the most important condition for choosing the flat is the town it is located in. This information is located at the end of oddaja_v_na column, so letâ€™s extract the last word from it in order to get the town :

#ensuring there are no extra spaces
data$oddaja_v_na<-str_trim(data$oddaja_v_na)

data$town <- sapply(strsplit(data$oddaja_v_na, "\\s+"), function(x) ifelse(length(x) > 1, tail(x, 1), NA))
#since "NOVA GORICA" is the only town with 2 words, we have to change all GORICA entries to NOVA GORICA 
data<-data %>% 
   mutate(town = str_replace(town, "GORICA", "NOVA GORICA")) %>% 
  select(town, everything())

data %>% nice_table(.,5)

0.3 Filtering

Finally, in order to use the least time possible to find suitable flats (in towns with more than 1 flat per town), letâ€™s divide them by towns, extract only the ones that have gmail email provider (to assure correct contact) and arrange them by number of beds in each flat:

towns2<-filteredFlats%>%
  dplyr::filter(total_appearances != 1) %>%
  dplyr::filter(!(Å¡t__leÅ¾iÅ¡Ä %in% c("ZASEDENO", NA, ""))) %>% 
  na.omit %>% 
  distinct(town)


data2<-data %>% 
  dplyr::filter(town %in% towns2$town) %>% 
  dplyr::filter(email_provider == "gmail")

  
getFlatsByTown<-function(town_value) {
  data2 %>%
    dplyr::filter(town == town_value) %>%
    select(-town) %>% 
    arrange(desc(Å¡t__leÅ¾iÅ¡Ä)) %>% 
       nice_table(.,5)
}

0.4 Conclusion

If we assume that landlords are to be contacted by email first, most of the email entries can be confimed via gmail. Furthermore, most of the flats are located in Koper, which is to be expected since it is the largest town and most of the faculties are located there. The filtered tables can serve as a source for contacting the landlords to ask about available accomodation, and such a dataset can drastically save time in flat hunting compared to usual process which includes only websites such as mojcimer.si, where limited amount of landlords post ads for their flats.
